WEBVTT

00:02.502 --> 00:04.671
[***]

00:04.704 --> 00:06.639
[GAS HISSING]

00:10.210 --> 00:13.446
NARRATOR:
<i>My sister, Tonya, was the baby</i>
<i>of the family,</i>

00:13.480 --> 00:16.416
<i>so she was used to doing</i>
<i>whatever she felt like.</i>

00:21.688 --> 00:24.090
<i>When you have more kids</i>
<i>than parents,</i>

00:24.124 --> 00:25.725
<i>one of the kids gets a kid.</i>

00:25.759 --> 00:27.360
<i>I got Tonya.</i>

00:44.577 --> 00:45.645
Are you crazy?

00:45.679 --> 00:47.447
I was trying to make
hot chocolate!

00:47.480 --> 00:48.882
That's not
the way you do it.

00:48.915 --> 00:50.550
Why don't you ask
somebody for help

00:50.583 --> 00:52.352
before you start
messing things up?

00:52.385 --> 00:53.520
And give me the matches.

00:53.553 --> 00:55.522
Are you trying to blow
the house up?

00:55.555 --> 00:57.223
ROCHELLE:
Chris, I smell...

01:02.395 --> 01:03.396
No!

01:03.430 --> 01:05.365
Goodness, boy,
are you crazy?

01:05.398 --> 01:07.600
Are you trying
to blow the whole house up?

01:07.634 --> 01:09.269
I tried to tell him.

01:09.302 --> 01:11.771
NARRATOR:
<i>Little sisters.</i>
<i>You can't live with them,</i>

01:11.805 --> 01:14.874
<i>and they can't accidentally</i>
<i>turn up missing.</i>

01:14.908 --> 01:17.243
[***]

01:22.882 --> 01:25.552
<i>* Aw, make it funky now </i>

01:49.509 --> 01:50.777
There you go.
<i>Daily News.</i>

01:50.810 --> 01:52.479
Here you go.
Thanks.

01:52.512 --> 01:54.881
Tonya was trying to light
the stove, but you got blamed?

01:54.914 --> 01:57.684
If that little girl coughs,
I got to cover my mouth.

01:57.717 --> 02:00.220
I think it's pretty cool
having a brother and sister.

02:00.253 --> 02:02.355
No, you're lucky
you're an only child.

02:02.389 --> 02:04.491
Yeah, I guess.
NARRATOR:<i>Brooklyn is filled</i>

02:04.524 --> 02:06.493
<i>with Blacks, Catholics,</i>
<i>and Puerto Ricans.</i>

02:06.526 --> 02:08.795
<i>Greg was probably</i>
<i>the only only child there.</i>

02:08.828 --> 02:11.197
It gets lonely once
in a while, you know.

02:11.231 --> 02:12.599
I don't have
to fight over the TV

02:12.632 --> 02:14.501
if I want to watch
a basketball game.

02:14.534 --> 02:16.336
At least you get
to watch a game.

02:16.369 --> 02:17.604
Every time I turn
on the TV,

02:17.637 --> 02:19.572
my sister wants
to watch the<i>Care Bears.</i>

02:19.606 --> 02:21.474
NARRATOR:
<i>Overrated show, by the way.</i>

02:21.508 --> 02:24.210
...having a little brother
and sister would be cool.

02:24.244 --> 02:25.645
I mean, instead,
I get toys.

02:25.679 --> 02:26.813
I got an Atari.

02:26.846 --> 02:28.615
Wait. You've got an Atari?

02:28.648 --> 02:31.451
NARRATOR:
<i>Atari was the PlayStation</i>
<i>of 1982.</i>

02:31.484 --> 02:33.520
<i>We got one in 1994.</i>

02:33.553 --> 02:35.622
<i>We didn't get a game till 1997.</i>

02:35.655 --> 02:37.223
Yep. Just got it.

02:37.257 --> 02:39.292
NARRATOR:
<i>We didn't have</i>
<i>any electronic games,</i>

02:39.325 --> 02:41.494
<i>but we had singing into a fan.</i>

02:41.528 --> 02:43.563
Who wants to play
Clean Up This Damn House?

02:43.596 --> 02:45.298
Me! Me!
NARRATOR:<i>I won</i>

02:45.331 --> 02:46.833
<i>the Take the Garbage Out</i>
<i>competition</i>

02:46.866 --> 02:48.535
<i>four years in a row.</i>

02:48.568 --> 02:50.403
Hey, you want to come over
to my house after school?

02:50.437 --> 02:52.272
Naw, I think
I should go home.

02:52.305 --> 02:53.540
Oh, come on.
Forget about it.

02:53.573 --> 02:55.675
I only live
a couple blocks away.

02:55.709 --> 02:57.010
Okay.

02:57.043 --> 02:59.646
NARRATOR:
<i>Just one game won't hurt,</i>
<i>right?</i>

02:59.679 --> 03:00.947
[DOOR OPENS]

03:00.980 --> 03:03.283
[***]

03:05.752 --> 03:07.420
Hey, baby.

03:07.454 --> 03:09.255
Hey, babe, how you doing?

03:09.289 --> 03:10.457
Good.

03:10.490 --> 03:12.292
You want something to eat?

03:12.325 --> 03:13.893
Aren't you supposed
to be at work?

03:13.927 --> 03:16.363
Oh, I have a little time off.

03:16.396 --> 03:18.298
NARRATOR:
<i>What actually happened was...</i>

03:18.331 --> 03:20.433
Excuse me. Do you have
these in a size eight?

03:20.467 --> 03:22.435
Do you see me helping
somebody else?

03:22.469 --> 03:23.737
All that hollering
at people.

03:23.770 --> 03:26.272
I do not need this.
My man has two jobs.

03:26.306 --> 03:27.907
And you ain't no damn eight.

03:27.941 --> 03:29.442
Get her an 11!

03:29.476 --> 03:30.844
Sure you don't want something?

03:30.877 --> 03:33.346
No, I grabbed some breakfast
with the guys.

03:33.380 --> 03:34.781
I'm pretty tired.

03:34.814 --> 03:37.484
I'm just gonna grab a shower
and get some sleep.

03:37.517 --> 03:38.585
Julius.

03:38.618 --> 03:39.552
Yeah?

03:39.586 --> 03:42.355
Well, I was just thinking, uh,

03:42.389 --> 03:44.057
since we have the house
to ourselves

03:44.090 --> 03:49.629
that maybe we can do some things
that we don't usually get to do.

03:51.364 --> 03:52.832
What do you have
in mind?

03:52.866 --> 03:53.900
[CHUCKLES]

03:53.933 --> 03:55.869
MAN:
<i>Come on down!</i>

03:55.902 --> 03:58.738
<i>You're the next contestant</i>
<i>on</i>The Price Is Right!

03:58.772 --> 04:00.507
NARRATOR:
<i>My dad liked game shows.</i>

04:00.540 --> 04:02.342
Come on, sister,
you can do it.

04:02.375 --> 04:04.678
NARRATOR:
<i>He always rooted</i>
<i>for the black people.</i>

04:04.711 --> 04:06.479
<i>If there were</i>
<i>no black people on it,</i>

04:06.513 --> 04:08.381
<i>then he'd root for</i>
<i>anybody with a tan.</i>

04:08.415 --> 04:11.017
<i>What's the next item</i>
<i>up for bids, please?</i>

04:11.051 --> 04:13.687
ANNOUNCER:
<i>A new dishwasher.</i>

04:13.720 --> 04:15.522
$430.

04:15.555 --> 04:17.657
<i>I want the first bid</i>
<i>from Bennett.</i>

04:17.691 --> 04:19.492
<i>$400.</i>
<i>$400.</i>

04:19.526 --> 04:21.761
That's good.
That's right. You right.

04:21.795 --> 04:22.929
<i>$625.</i>

04:22.962 --> 04:25.031
Ooh, you're a fool
if you pay that much.

04:25.065 --> 04:26.666
<i>$580.</i>

04:26.700 --> 04:29.569
What is a man doing there
11:00 in the morning?

04:29.602 --> 04:31.638
He got no job?
[CHUCKLES]

04:31.671 --> 04:32.806
<i>$430.</i>

04:32.839 --> 04:34.708
NARRATOR:
<i>My father was like Rain Man</i>

04:34.741 --> 04:36.910
<i>when it came to guessing</i>
<i>how much something cost.</i>

04:36.943 --> 04:39.879
How did you know that?
We don't even own a dishwasher.

04:39.913 --> 04:41.114
That's 'cause it cost $430.

04:41.147 --> 04:42.882
[***]

04:42.916 --> 04:45.018
NARRATOR:
<i>Greg's house</i>
<i>was a lot different</i>

04:45.051 --> 04:46.653
<i>than what I expected.</i>

04:46.686 --> 04:48.355
<i>I used to think</i>
<i>all white people were rich.</i>

04:48.388 --> 04:50.523
<i>I thought his house</i>
<i>would look more like this.</i>

04:50.557 --> 04:54.461
LEACH:
<i>And the Wuligers parlayed</i>
<i>their fortune into millions,</i>

04:54.494 --> 04:58.365
<i>and this fabulous estate</i>
<i>in Brooklyn.</i>

04:58.398 --> 05:01.401
[GAME CHIMING]

05:01.434 --> 05:03.770
I hate these
plastic covers,

05:03.803 --> 05:05.538
especially
in the summer.

05:05.572 --> 05:07.741
They get your legs all sweaty
and make 'em stick.

05:07.774 --> 05:10.143
My mom used to love
plastic covers so much,

05:10.176 --> 05:11.578
she'd put on a second set

05:11.611 --> 05:13.680
to make sure
the first set looked nice.

05:13.713 --> 05:15.382
[CHUCKLES]

05:15.415 --> 05:16.716
Hey, where's your mom?

05:16.750 --> 05:18.585
I live with my dad.
They split up.

05:18.618 --> 05:20.453
My dad said they really
didn't get along.

05:20.487 --> 05:22.856
NARRATOR:
<i>Actually, she ran off</i>
<i>with Greg's uncle,</i>

05:22.889 --> 05:25.592
<i>but that's another episode</i>
<i>on a different show.</i>

05:26.693 --> 05:29.662
Yes!
That's all right.

05:29.696 --> 05:31.831
You better be happy
I don't have one of these,

05:31.865 --> 05:33.600
or else I'd be
tearing you up.

05:35.535 --> 05:37.637
I got to go.

05:37.671 --> 05:40.407
Hey, you want to come back over
to my house tomorrow?

05:40.440 --> 05:42.575
Man, you lucky
I'm leaving now.

05:42.609 --> 05:44.477
I'll see you
tomorrow.

05:46.446 --> 05:49.582
NARRATOR:
<i>When my mother was gossiping,</i>
<i>nothing else mattered,</i>

05:49.616 --> 05:51.451
<i>even my father sleeping.</i>

05:51.484 --> 05:54.487
So he takes you to dinner,
uh-huh, and orders

05:54.521 --> 05:57.424
a two-for-one special
and then he said what?

05:57.457 --> 06:00.593
Rochelle, Rochelle.
Huh?

06:00.627 --> 06:02.629
I got to go to work
in a few hours, okay?

06:02.662 --> 06:04.864
Oh, I'm sorry, baby.
Okay.

06:04.898 --> 06:06.733
All right. Stop!

06:06.766 --> 06:08.201
Julius, you got
to hear this.

06:08.234 --> 06:10.470
You know that guy Marcus
that works for UPS

06:10.503 --> 06:11.871
with the stinky cologne?
Mm-hmm.

06:11.905 --> 06:13.707
He took Sheila
to the movies,

06:13.740 --> 06:15.975
bought this big ol' thing
of popcorn, two hot dogs.

06:16.009 --> 06:18.144
She asked him just
for a little piece,

06:18.178 --> 06:19.679
he told her no.
Two of 'em.

06:19.713 --> 06:21.581
Uh-huh. Sheila said hi, baby.

06:21.614 --> 06:22.982
Hey, Sheila.

06:23.016 --> 06:24.150
Girl, he trying to sleep.

06:24.184 --> 06:26.052
Uh-huh, he better
have big feet

06:26.086 --> 06:27.587
being that cheap.

06:27.620 --> 06:29.155
NARRATOR:
<i>My dad hated losing sleep,</i>

06:29.189 --> 06:30.924
<i>but he was happy when she</i>
<i>talked to her girlfriends.</i>

06:30.957 --> 06:32.726
<i>That way,</i>
<i>he didn't have to do it.</i>

06:32.759 --> 06:35.161
Julius, you are not
going to believe this.

06:35.195 --> 06:36.863
But you know that girl
Jody Watley

06:36.896 --> 06:38.732
that used to be
on<i>Soul Train?</i>

06:38.765 --> 06:40.900
I heard that she's leaving
the group Shalamar

06:40.934 --> 06:43.536
and starting a new group
with Ashford and Simpson.

06:43.570 --> 06:45.972
Can you believe that?
That's something.

06:46.006 --> 06:47.741
Ain't it?
Mm-hmm.

06:47.774 --> 06:49.542
NARRATOR:
<i>I stopped listening</i>
<i>at Jody Watley.</i>

06:49.576 --> 06:53.446
Uh-huh. Right, uh-huh.

06:54.147 --> 06:55.915
Julius, do you smell smoke?

06:55.949 --> 06:57.884
No. We having smoke?

06:57.917 --> 06:59.853
Oh, no,
you're trying to sleep.

06:59.886 --> 07:01.688
Chris!

07:02.989 --> 07:05.125
Uh, Sheila,
let me call you back.

07:05.158 --> 07:07.560
Okay. Chris!

07:07.594 --> 07:09.195
[COUGHING]

07:09.229 --> 07:11.531
What in the world?

07:11.564 --> 07:12.866
Move, girl!

07:12.899 --> 07:14.801
Oh!

07:14.834 --> 07:17.070
Tonya, what are you doing?

07:17.103 --> 07:18.238
Chris did it.

07:18.271 --> 07:19.973
Chris!

07:20.006 --> 07:21.574
Chris isn't here.

07:21.608 --> 07:22.642
Well, where is he?

07:22.676 --> 07:23.910
DREW:
I don't know.

07:23.943 --> 07:26.680
Who put this pot on the stove?
Wasn't me.

07:26.713 --> 07:30.250
NARRATOR:
<i>Because of those two words,</i>
<i>Drew never got in trouble.</i>

07:31.651 --> 07:34.087
Who tore up my back seat?

07:34.120 --> 07:35.588
Wasn't me.

07:35.622 --> 07:37.824
[***]

07:37.857 --> 07:41.227
Who left my nickel laying
out here on the sidewalk?

07:41.261 --> 07:44.230
Wasn't me.

07:44.264 --> 07:46.266
Who spilt this oatmeal?

07:46.299 --> 07:48.234
Wasn't me.

07:48.268 --> 07:51.838
NARRATOR:
<i>Would you believe</i>
<i>those were his first words?</i>

07:51.871 --> 07:54.674
Tanya, what is this mess, girl?

07:54.708 --> 07:57.610
I was trying
to make hot chocolate.

07:59.012 --> 08:02.182
I don't want you fooling around
with this hot chocolate again,

08:02.215 --> 08:03.717
do you hear me?

08:03.750 --> 08:06.119
Now get upstairs
before I make your behind hot!

08:06.152 --> 08:09.689
NARRATOR:
<i>I thought I'd see</i>
<i>George Bush in a do-rag</i>

08:09.723 --> 08:12.792
<i>before Tonya got in trouble.</i>

08:12.826 --> 08:15.128
And where were you?
You're late.

08:15.161 --> 08:16.863
My bus broke down.

08:16.896 --> 08:19.165
Next time, you better get off
and fix it.

08:19.199 --> 08:20.900
Yes, ma'am.

08:20.934 --> 08:23.603
NARRATOR:
<i>All right, I admit it.</i>
<i>I'm hooked.</i>

08:23.636 --> 08:24.838
Man, it felt so good

08:24.871 --> 08:27.640
to see Tonya get
in trouble yesterday.

08:27.674 --> 08:28.842
What'd they do to her?

08:28.875 --> 08:30.610
My mom knocked
all her teeth out.

08:30.643 --> 08:31.978
Really?

08:32.012 --> 08:34.014
Nah, she just sent her
upstairs to her room,

08:34.047 --> 08:36.783
but I wish she would have
smacked her teeth out.

08:36.816 --> 08:39.753
Yes!

08:39.786 --> 08:41.287
Oh, man, it's 4:30.

08:41.321 --> 08:43.623
4:30! You got to go!

08:43.656 --> 08:45.759
I'm not supposed
to have any company over.

08:45.792 --> 08:47.360
If my dad finds out
you're in here,

08:47.394 --> 08:49.195
he's going to kill me.

08:49.229 --> 08:51.031
No! You got to hide!

08:51.064 --> 08:52.766
Hide? I can't hide.
I got to go.

08:52.799 --> 08:54.968
If I don't get home,
my mom's going to kill me.

08:55.001 --> 08:57.170
Chris, I'm serious.
Please, you gotta hide.

08:57.203 --> 09:00.907
NARRATOR:
<i>Greg looked at me</i>
<i>like his father was Ike Turner.</i>

09:00.940 --> 09:02.676
Go, go, go!

09:05.979 --> 09:06.946
Get in there.

09:06.980 --> 09:08.615
As soon as the coast
is clear,

09:08.648 --> 09:09.983
I'll sneak you
out the back.

09:12.819 --> 09:14.788
Who you talking to?

09:14.821 --> 09:16.823
I'm talking to myself.

09:16.856 --> 09:18.825
You lonely?
I'll get you a gerbil.

09:18.858 --> 09:20.960
Now get ready
for dinner.

09:22.195 --> 09:24.798
[***]

09:24.831 --> 09:26.399
I gotta get out of here.

09:26.433 --> 09:31.771
<i>* Everybody hates Chris </i>

09:38.211 --> 09:40.113
When's Chris coming home?

09:40.146 --> 09:41.414
I don't know. Why?

09:41.448 --> 09:43.683
I want to cut the hair
off my doll's head,

09:43.717 --> 09:45.785
but I don't want to do it
till he gets here.

09:45.819 --> 09:47.854
NARRATOR:
<i>Without me</i>
<i>in the house to blame,</i>

09:47.887 --> 09:49.389
<i>Tonya actually</i>
<i>had to act right.</i>

09:49.422 --> 09:50.924
Is Chris here yet?

09:50.957 --> 09:52.125
Nope.

09:52.158 --> 09:53.626
Dang!

09:55.428 --> 09:57.163
Is Chris home yet?

09:57.197 --> 09:59.299
No.
Dang!

09:59.332 --> 10:03.169
Is Chris here yet?

10:03.203 --> 10:05.905
No.
Dang!

10:05.939 --> 10:09.376
I'll sure be glad
when Chris gets back.

10:11.077 --> 10:12.779
Chris?

10:17.117 --> 10:18.118
Chris?

10:19.886 --> 10:21.921
NARRATOR:
<i>While I was hiding</i>
<i>in the closet,</i>

10:21.955 --> 10:23.423
<i>the only thing</i>
<i>I could think about</i>

10:23.456 --> 10:26.826
<i>was getting the hell</i>
<i>out of there and getting home.</i>

10:39.472 --> 10:42.809
<i>The biggest difference between</i>
<i>being in a black neighborhood</i>

10:42.842 --> 10:44.244
<i>and a white neighborhood is</i>

10:44.277 --> 10:46.212
<i>the black guys'll</i>
<i>beat you up and rob you.</i>

10:46.246 --> 10:48.014
<i>The white guys'll</i>
<i>just beat you up.</i>

10:48.048 --> 10:49.849
<i>Even though I was scared,</i>
<i>I figured</i>

10:49.883 --> 10:51.384
<i>the best way</i>
<i>to get through this</i>

10:51.418 --> 10:53.153
<i>was to act like I belonged.</i>

10:53.186 --> 10:55.155
[***]

11:05.298 --> 11:06.966
Get out of here.

11:07.000 --> 11:08.401
Hey!

11:08.435 --> 11:10.170
Yeah, what have we
got here, huh?

11:10.203 --> 11:12.072
What are you
doing, huh?

11:12.105 --> 11:14.407
Ah, forget about it,
little watermelon.

11:14.441 --> 11:16.409
Keep walking!
You got to keep right.

11:16.443 --> 11:18.978
NARRATOR:
<i>Where do they</i>
<i>come up with this stuff?</i>

11:19.012 --> 11:20.413
No fried chicken
around here.

11:20.447 --> 11:21.881
He's right!

11:21.915 --> 11:24.050
Get on out of here.
Watch your back.

11:24.084 --> 11:26.920
Go back to your
black neighborhood, kid.

11:30.190 --> 11:31.424
Geez.

11:31.458 --> 11:34.994
Gregory, you got dents
all in my sofa.

11:35.028 --> 11:37.030
Can you sit
in one spot,

11:37.063 --> 11:41.501
and can you drink
out of one glass?

11:45.805 --> 11:48.208
NARRATOR:
<i>This is like</i>CSI: Brooklyn.

11:48.241 --> 11:50.143
Gregory...

11:50.176 --> 11:52.045
did you have
somebody over here?

11:52.078 --> 11:56.116
I told you, no company
when I'm not here.

11:56.149 --> 11:58.885
Dad, I had my friend Chris
over after school.

11:58.918 --> 12:00.387
We played video games
and stuff.

12:00.420 --> 12:02.956
The next time you want
to have somebody in here

12:02.989 --> 12:05.058
you ask first, you understand?

12:05.091 --> 12:06.226
Dad...

12:08.361 --> 12:09.396
He's still here.

12:09.429 --> 12:11.531
[***]

12:15.301 --> 12:16.302
ROCHELLE:
Chris?

12:16.336 --> 12:18.338
Chris is home!

12:18.371 --> 12:20.306
[SCISSORS SNIPPING]

12:27.013 --> 12:28.348
Is Chris here yet?

12:28.381 --> 12:29.349
No.

12:29.382 --> 12:31.084
Hmm.

12:34.554 --> 12:36.356
Who cut your doll's hair off?

12:36.389 --> 12:37.557
Wasn't me.

12:41.227 --> 12:42.228
Julius, wake up.

12:42.262 --> 12:44.497
I know. Give me
five more minutes.

12:44.531 --> 12:46.099
Julius.

12:46.132 --> 12:48.835
$1762.95.

12:48.868 --> 12:50.303
Julius!

12:50.337 --> 12:51.504
What?

12:51.538 --> 12:53.606
Did you win?
Chris isn't home yet.

12:53.640 --> 12:55.909
Did you check his room?

12:55.942 --> 12:57.844
ROCHELLE:
I looked all over the house.

12:57.877 --> 12:59.045
He's not here.

12:59.079 --> 13:01.247
He should have been home
a long time ago.

13:01.281 --> 13:03.216
[***]

13:05.885 --> 13:07.587
Do you think
Chris is dead?

13:07.620 --> 13:10.290
NARRATOR:
<i>In my neighborhood,</i>
<i>being 15 minutes late</i>

13:10.323 --> 13:12.592
<i>could mean you're dead.</i>

13:12.625 --> 13:13.860
He's not dead.

13:13.893 --> 13:15.195
He's just late.

13:16.029 --> 13:18.131
[CHRIS SCREAMING]

13:19.499 --> 13:21.901
NARRATOR:
<i>Still not dead.</i>

13:25.271 --> 13:27.173
ART:
Hey.

13:27.207 --> 13:28.141
Chris.

13:28.174 --> 13:29.609
Art, do you know
this kid?

13:29.642 --> 13:30.944
Yeah, sure.

13:34.481 --> 13:36.049
You know that guy?

13:40.320 --> 13:41.421
Let's go.

13:41.454 --> 13:43.390
[SCREAMING]

13:47.160 --> 13:48.028
Get in.

13:48.061 --> 13:50.296
MAN:
No! Help me!

13:50.330 --> 13:52.198
[MAN SCREAMING]

13:55.935 --> 13:58.104
Did he say he was doing
something after school?

13:58.138 --> 14:01.174
No. He was just supposed
to pick up my dry cleaning.

14:01.207 --> 14:03.576
Maybe it wasn't done yet.

14:03.610 --> 14:05.578
I'll see if he's over there.

14:05.612 --> 14:07.947
[***]

14:19.192 --> 14:20.427
Chris!

14:20.460 --> 14:21.928
Chris, oh, thank goodness.

14:21.961 --> 14:23.196
Are you okay?
Yeah, I'm okay.

14:23.229 --> 14:25.365
Oh, I'm so happy
you're all right.

14:25.398 --> 14:28.034
I'm gonna kill you!
Where you been, boy?

14:28.968 --> 14:29.936
Who are you?

14:29.969 --> 14:31.471
Wuliger. Art Wuliger.

14:31.504 --> 14:33.239
I'm Greg's dad.
Greg who?

14:33.273 --> 14:35.709
I'm Greg.
We go to school together.

14:35.742 --> 14:37.177
[SIGHS]

14:37.210 --> 14:39.079
Greg asked me to come over
after school.

14:39.112 --> 14:40.714
We were just hanging out.

14:40.747 --> 14:42.615
[MOCKINGLY]
Oh, "We were just hanging out."

14:42.649 --> 14:44.684
I'm over here worried sick,
and you were hanging out?

14:44.718 --> 14:46.219
Have you lost your mind?

14:46.252 --> 14:47.587
If you're gonna go over
to somebody's house,

14:47.620 --> 14:49.055
you got to let
somebody know.

14:49.089 --> 14:51.024
They don't have a phone
at Greg's house?

14:51.057 --> 14:52.292
I don't care
where you are.

14:52.325 --> 14:54.260
You be like E.T.,
you phone home!

14:54.294 --> 14:56.096
I need to know
where you are,

14:56.129 --> 14:58.298
who you're with
and what you're doing.

14:58.331 --> 15:00.266
How do I know you're not
selling drugs?

15:00.300 --> 15:01.735
I mean,
you could be kingpin

15:01.768 --> 15:03.570
of a Columbian drug cartel
for all I know.

15:03.603 --> 15:06.973
I'm not out there selling drugs.
How do I know that?

15:07.007 --> 15:09.209
NARRATOR:
<i>My mother had</i>
<i>one goal in life</i>

15:09.242 --> 15:10.543
<i>for her kids:</i>
<i>don't sell drugs.</i>

15:10.577 --> 15:12.379
<i>As long as they weren't</i>
<i>doing that,</i>

15:12.412 --> 15:14.414
<i>almost everything else</i>
<i>was okay.</i>

15:16.149 --> 15:17.751
Ma'am, your son
shot the mayor.

15:17.784 --> 15:19.419
Did he sell drugs?
No.

15:19.452 --> 15:21.221
Get in here, boy.

15:22.522 --> 15:24.524
Your son killed the governor,
kidnapped his daughter,

15:24.557 --> 15:26.126
robbed the president
and ran a red light.

15:26.159 --> 15:28.294
He ain't sell no drugs, did he?
No, ma'am.

15:28.328 --> 15:30.030
Boy, get in here.

15:32.499 --> 15:33.667
Upstairs.

15:33.700 --> 15:35.035
Right now.

15:35.068 --> 15:36.469
Is Chris gonna
get in trouble?

15:36.503 --> 15:38.104
Is that your business?

15:41.241 --> 15:42.008
Hey...

15:42.042 --> 15:45.045
Thanks for bringing him home.
Yeah.

15:45.078 --> 15:48.214
Next time, keep
a better eye on your kid.

15:50.450 --> 15:51.651
Hey.

15:51.685 --> 15:53.453
What you trying to say?

15:53.486 --> 15:54.721
I'm just saying,

15:54.754 --> 15:57.657
I'm on my own, I work,
I got my own kid.

15:57.691 --> 16:00.326
You think I got time
to run around the neighborhood

16:00.360 --> 16:02.629
looking for your kid?
I said thank you.

16:02.662 --> 16:04.197
What you want, a cookie?

16:04.230 --> 16:05.432
NARRATOR:
<i>He did sort of want a cookie.</i>

16:05.465 --> 16:07.334
Your boy's the one
had him over there.

16:07.367 --> 16:09.069
Oh, he didn't kidnap him.

16:10.303 --> 16:11.671
Know what?

16:11.705 --> 16:14.441
You don't have to worry
about Chris from here on out.

16:14.474 --> 16:17.644
That sounds like the best idea
I've heard all night.

16:17.677 --> 16:19.579
Come on, Greg.

16:19.612 --> 16:22.248
[***]

16:22.282 --> 16:23.416
Gregory.

16:33.493 --> 16:34.728
Hey.

16:34.761 --> 16:36.596
You get in
a lot of trouble?

16:36.629 --> 16:38.298
My dad grounded me.

16:38.331 --> 16:40.467
Plus, he took away
my Atari for a week.

16:40.500 --> 16:41.601
How about you?

16:41.634 --> 16:43.570
My mom said that if I ever
did that again

16:43.603 --> 16:45.505
she'd slap all
the tartar off my teeth.

16:45.538 --> 16:47.841
Plus, my dad says I can't
come over anymore.

16:47.874 --> 16:49.442
Lucky for you,

16:49.476 --> 16:51.845
'cause next time we played,
I was gonna stomp you.

16:51.878 --> 16:54.214
Man, you wish.

16:57.517 --> 16:59.119
Well, see ya.

16:59.853 --> 17:02.355
Yeah. See ya.

17:04.157 --> 17:06.259
[***]

17:15.168 --> 17:17.170
[DOOR CLOSES]

17:18.538 --> 17:19.572
Hey.

17:19.606 --> 17:22.375
Your dad said you couldn't
come over to my house.

17:22.409 --> 17:24.611
He didn't say I couldn't
come over to yours.

17:27.414 --> 17:29.516
[BEATBOXING, DISTORTED]

17:39.292 --> 17:42.662
NARRATOR:
<i>Even though we were spending</i>
<i>12 cents' worth of electricity,</i>

17:42.696 --> 17:45.265
<i>my father thought</i>
<i>it was worth it.</i>

17:45.298 --> 17:47.400
[CONTINUES BEATBOXING]

17:49.903 --> 17:51.671
[DOOR CLOSES]

17:51.705 --> 17:52.839
Greg?

17:55.742 --> 17:57.310
Hey, Dad.

18:00.213 --> 18:01.648
What's this?

18:01.681 --> 18:03.249
How you doing?

18:03.283 --> 18:05.218
GREG:
I went over
to Chris's house.

18:05.251 --> 18:06.653
His dad brought
me home.

18:08.188 --> 18:10.857
Look, I think we got off
on the wrong foot.

18:12.325 --> 18:15.495
I just didn't want that
to get in the way of the boys.

18:17.664 --> 18:19.599
You two are real buddies, huh?

18:19.632 --> 18:21.568
Yeah.
Yeah.

18:21.601 --> 18:24.704
JULIUS:
Anyway, I just
wanted to make sure

18:24.738 --> 18:26.940
Greg made it home okay.

18:26.973 --> 18:28.441
Yeah. Thanks.

18:28.475 --> 18:31.177
Hey, Dad, can Chris
stay for a little while?

18:31.211 --> 18:33.213
[***]

18:34.514 --> 18:35.548
Yeah, sure.

18:40.420 --> 18:42.789
Julius,
you a beer-drinking man?

18:42.822 --> 18:44.357
Is it cold?

18:45.558 --> 18:46.893
Come on.

18:46.926 --> 18:49.229
[***]

18:52.766 --> 18:55.902
NARRATOR:
<i>After that, things kind</i>
<i>of went back to normal.</i>

18:55.935 --> 18:57.604
<i>Mom started working again.</i>

18:57.637 --> 18:59.639
<i>So she let Dad</i>
<i>get some sleep.</i>

18:59.673 --> 19:02.342
<i>Drew still didn't get blamed</i>
<i>for anything,</i>

19:02.375 --> 19:04.310
<i>and even thought Tonya</i>
<i>got on my nerves,</i>

19:04.344 --> 19:07.580
<i>I thought maybe it was time</i>
<i>to do something nice for her.</i>

19:07.614 --> 19:10.283
Now that's how
you make hot chocolate.

19:10.316 --> 19:11.685
Thanks, Chris.

19:13.319 --> 19:15.555
Uh-uh. What are you doing?
Having hot chocolate.

19:15.588 --> 19:17.924
I told her she couldn't
have any hot chocolate.

19:17.957 --> 19:19.526
That's what I tried
to tell him.

19:19.559 --> 19:24.264
<i>* Everybody hates Chris </i>

19:27.967 --> 19:31.404
NARRATOR:
<i>Stay tuned for scenes</i>
<i>from our next episode.</i>

19:33.340 --> 19:35.442
[***]
